# Best Practices for Teaching with micro:bit

#### Physical computing is a fun and hands-on way to engage students in coding, however, there are some things to consider to make sure your lessons run smoothly. 

## Before the lesson

<details style="background-color: #ececec; padding: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; border: 1px solid transparent; border-radius: 5px;">
    <summary style="font-size: 1.5em; font-weight: bold;">🗃️ Organization tips</summary>
<div style="margin-top: 20px; margin-left: 20px; margin-right: 20px;">
    <p>


<img src="https://images.code.org/8c5598c604dc9e7a0e4edcf01d5b7244-image-1707322034881.png" alt="storage container for micro:bit" width="250px" style="border-radius:10px; float:right; margin: 0 40px 80px 40px;">

- #### Labeling the micro:bit is a simple way to assign them and count them in and out.

- #### Use the original anti-static pouch to store the micro:bits to protect the device.

- #### To store multiple micro:bits, there exists a multitude of creative options. Containers can be purchased to store micro:bits and their accessories. 
</p></div>
</details>

<details style="background-color: #ececec; padding: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; border: 1px solid transparent; border-radius: 5px;">
    <summary style="font-size: 1.5em; font-weight: bold;">✍🏽 Preparation </summary>
<div style="margin-top: 20px; margin-left: 20px; margin-right: 20px;">
    <p>

<img src="https://images.code.org/a99418675b349371703fe1ed4b821fc4-image-1707407730242.png" alt="two micro:bits with faces" width="250px" style="border-radius:10px; float:right; margin: 0 40px 0px 40px;">

- #### **Read over the lesson plan first.**Take the time to get familiar with the lesson and anticipate where students might need extra support. 

- #### Plan for how the devices you have will be distributed among your students. 

- #### Practice the lesson.  
</p></div>
</details>


## During the lesson

<details style="background-color: #ececec; padding: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; border: 1px solid transparent; border-radius: 5px;">
    <summary style="font-size: 1.5em; font-weight: bold;">💭 Relate to familiar concepts </summary>
<div style="margin-top: 20px; margin-left: 20px; margin-right: 20px;">
    <p>

<img src="https://images.code.org/f97e7a0677c60156fdd380843c4fc2ea-image-1707322374547.png" alt="micro:bit on a shoe with a one on it" width="175px" style="border-radius:10px; float:right; margin: 0 40px 20px 40px;">

- #### Use everyday examples and real-world context to explain the concepts of inputs and outputs in a way that is relatable to their experiences.

- #### Review coding concepts like that have been learned in class and remind students that these concepts carry over when coding their micro:bits. 


</p></div>
</details>

<details style="background-color: #ececec; padding: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; border: 1px solid transparent; border-radius: 5px;">
    <summary style="font-size: 1.5em; font-weight: bold;">🎨 Encourage Creativity </summary>
<div style="margin-top: 20px; margin-left: 20px; margin-right: 20px;">
    <p>

<img src="https://images.code.org/613d33bfaf85b3d47b95e2ad96c84c8d-image-1707323049639.png" alt="students holding a micro:bit" width="175px" style="border-radius:10px; float:right; margin: 0 40px 0px 40px;">


- #### Unlike some of the coding levels on the Code.org platform, MakeCode does not have validation to “pass.” 
- #### Encourage students to be creative and explore the possibilities. 
- #### Celebrate perserverance and trying new things, even if it doesn't always work.

</p></div>
</details>

<details style="background-color: #ececec; padding: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; border: 1px solid transparent; border-radius: 5px;">
    <summary style="font-size: 1.5em; font-weight: bold;">🧑‍🏫 Facilitating the Lesson </summary>
<div style="margin-top: 20px; margin-left: 20px; margin-right: 20px;">
    <p>

<img src="https://images.code.org/0fa0e524a2e581105f69df060126cf8c-image-1707408688944.png" alt="students holding a micro:bit" width="250px" style="border-radius:10px; float:right; margin: 0 40px 0px 40px;">

- #### **Use the virtual micro:bit.** Makecode has a virtual micro:bit embedded on the site. This is a great tool if you have limited devices or if you want students to practice coding first. 

- #### **Implement pair programming strategies.** Assign one student to be the driver and another as the navigator. Set a timer and allow the students to switch roles. 

- #### **Encourage discussion.** Enrich students’ experience with by building in discussion and sharing amongst students. Students can share or demo their projects, discuss what was easy/challenging and what they liked best about the experience. 
</p></div>
</details>
 

